  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>What breaks — inverter drives, coin mechanisms, door gaskets</h2>
    <p>Across our Dexter Commercial service volume, the failure mix overlaps substantially with Speed Queen and other Alliance-family equipment — commercial laundry mechanics are similar across manufacturers. Three domains concentrate most of the Dexter call work.</p>
    <p><b>Inverter drive faults</b> on T-Series soft-mount and O-Series front-loads follow the standard commercial laundry pattern. After LA brownout events or hard mid-cycle shutoffs, the VFD on the main motor can throw overcurrent trips on restart, drive-to-panel communication losses, or voltage-sag lockouts. Diagnostic sequence: read panel fault code, cycle the main disconnect for full drive reset, tighten the drive-to-motor output terminals, verify voltage-sag threshold settings against LA brownout conditions, test motor winding resistance. Most fault calls resolve at reset + tightening; drive replacement needed roughly 10-15% of cases.</p>
    <p><b>Coin mechanism wear</b> concentrates on T-Series coin-op variants. Coin drops jam from bent coins and accumulated grit; coin slide mechanisms wear out after several thousand cycles. Card-reader retrofit to ESD, Card Concepts, CleanCloud, or Cents is a recurring project type we coordinate with the card-system vendor. Vandalism-repair patterns depend on laundromat location and surveillance coverage.</p>
    <p><b>Door gasket replacements</b> on high-cycle O-Series and T-Series front-loads are the routine consumable. Door gaskets compress and deform over 20,000+ cycles; early signs are door-close resistance changes and small water leaks at the bottom of the door frame during spin. Replacement is a straightforward service call at $220-$380 typical.</p>
  </div></section>

